The Peer Device MUST Match
This is the #1 reason LACP fails when adding members. 
The device on the other end of the cables (the peer switch/router) 
must have the exact same number of ports added to its corresponding LACP LAG.
If your switch has 4 ports in the LAG, but the peer switch only has 3 ports in its LAG, 
the LACP negotiation will fail, and the ports will likely be suspended or blocked.

Port Configuration Must Be Identical
All member ports in the LAG must have the exact same configuration. 
Before adding a new port, ensure it matches the existing members in:
-Speed and Duplex: (e.g., all must be 10Gbps Full-Duplex. 
  LACP will not bundle a 1G port with a 10G port).
-VLANs: The allowed VLANs, native VLAN (PVID),
  and VLAN tagging modes must be identical.
-MTU: The Maximum Transmission Unit size must match.
-Other settings: Flow control, link debounce, 
 and QoS policies should be identical.
